<br>
I wasn't implying or saying that.  No where in my posts did I say that.  I'm just passing on information that I thought was somewhat relevant as I remember a discussion about cars a month or so on one of the general forums.<br>
<br>
Personally I think it's just good Public Relations for the US automakers.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uraedwulf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raedwulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 291<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/29/01 7:45:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=199.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> I support Honda for they employ more Americans per car sold than any of the Big Three.  My cousin works for all 3 in an outsourcing industry that provides the foam padding for the seats.  All of his product is shipped elsewhere for installation into the cars.  I forget if it's GM or Ford, but most of their cars are assembled in Mexico.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, all three Hondas I've purchased in the last 11 years were assembled in Ohio from parts that were mostly made in America.<br>
<br>
Sure there's good ol' Patriotic passion behind some of the donations, but there's also lots of marketing in a time where there is a very hard sell on &quot;American&quot; products.  Please don't check your brain at the door when making a purchase.<br>
<br>
Buy Honda.  More Americans will benefit from it than if you bought a Ford. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uealan01.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ealan01</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 201<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/29/01 11:16:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=199.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> I'd double-check that statistic about where the parts are made.  Assembly is one thing, but I have never heard of Japanese car manufacturers making actual parts here.<br>
<br>
Also, how much of a career path, beyond the line, does an American worker have in Honda?  I am honestly curious.  Don't forget, the reason Japanese companies build plants here is because it is *cheaper* than in Japan (I know that for a fact; we are the &quot;Mexico&quot; of Japan).  Lets also not forget that supporting Honda does absolutely zilch for the US GNP which is the direct measure of our economy and is the measure by which everyone gets to decide whether or not we have finally entered the dreaded recession that they all love predicting.  Don't buy American?  Sure, do what you want, but lets not try to pretend that buying foreign brands actually *helps* our economy because it doesn't.<br>
<br>
As far as &quot;would our companies donate if this happened elsewhere?&quot;.  I am positive they would.  Disasters have happened in other parts of the world (natural and otherwise) and American companies have donated millions.  And it obviously wasn't about &quot;marketing&quot; since you have heard nothing about it.<br>
<br>
Too much cynicism is a bad thing.  Why isn't any of that cynicism turned on the companies that *didn't* donate?  American companies are donating for PR and Japanese companies *aren't* donating why, exactly? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ubelgarbattlebiztch.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Belgar Battlebiztch</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 71<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/29/01 11:23:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=199.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> Like the post.  I live in a town where  &quot;Ford&quot; Dealership is the biggest.  They've been doing a Lot of promotion on  feeding the economy here.  And offering some phenominal deals.  Knew they'd contributed, because the owner is BIG (HUGE) into the community charities.<br>
<br>
Curious, what's  Micro-shaft, I mean soft doing ?<br>
<br>
Also took a look at one of the biggest employers here, Raytheon.  They've donated I think 3 mil, jets, recovery cameras, and set up funds for the Raytheon families that were impacted.<br>
<br>
Nice to see who cares, is all. <p><Center><IMG SRC="http://www.lof.ukhq.co.uk/sigs/belgar.jpg"><BR><IT>
54th Level, Officer of "The Legion of Fate", Shaman Tank 
BattleBizitch, Heyokah!
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uraedwulf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raedwulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 292<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/30/01 1:08:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=199.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> My wife's 96 Civic contains 60% American made parts.  I understand the difference between simple assembly and actually being made here.  I looked up the stats when we bought it.  [I was gonna buy a Honda anyway since they are built a heck of a lot better than others.]<br>
<br>
As for GDP, the name of the company is American Honda Co.  They pay tons of taxes and are in our GDP.  Sure, the top of the company is in Japan, but there are huge numbers of Americans in management, not just on the assembly line.<br>
<br>
Sure, our multi-national corporations have donated in other parts of the world, but guess what?  They are in those markets, too, so those donations have a marketting effect there.  The fact that you knew about them, as did I, suggests that they aren't exactly keeping the left hand from knowing what the right hand is doing.<br>
<br>
